	   <tr><td colspan=2>You are right in correcting Illia in the misinformed coining of the term "shamen", but I must point out two errors of your own.<br><br>Granted, you allow for some wiggle-room by acknowledging that "Shama" is not the proper etymology of the word, but to get to the true linguistic core of the word one needs to dig deeper to find its' roots.&nbsp;&nbsp;"Saman" is actually the proper word, not the whale name you claim to be the true spelling.<br><br>The word shaman is derived from a word in the Tungusic language of Siberia, one of the areas in which the classical form of shamanism is found. Originally, it comes from the Evinki or Evenki (depending on your source) people of Siberia, and literally means "the one who knows" or "excited, frenzied person".<br><br>I think this accurately describes us in terms of the game since we are the wielders of primitive magic and are considered wise regardless of our level of intelligence.  And anyone who groups with me will attest to my fidgety and excitable nature when contfronted with a formidable enemy.<br><br>Now here is where your second error takes place: although I have been wrong in using the word "shamen" just as Illia has, judging by your use of a Roman citizen as an example, it would fall short of a complete explanation since you would not refer to a Roman woman as a Romaness even though a female shaman is called a "shamaness".   Hence, your example is inadequate.<br><br>I think if we are going to be picky about word smithing then striving to be precise is a quality we should attempt to attain, don't you agree, Mr. Anonymous?  Hmmmmmm?<br><br>--Pusbag Infection<br>&nbsp;<br>Emperor and Shamanic High Priest of the Trolls<br>"Worship Innoruuk, you worthless cattle!"<br></td></tr>
